transcription.text:
Speaker 1: Thank you for calling Viagra. How can I help you?

Speaker 2: Actually, I'm trying to get some information about your advertisement for the Viagra AGV.

Speaker 1: Sure, I can help you out with that.

Speaker 2: So we are the only company that's contracted directly with Pfizer with their manufacturer in France called Greenstone.

Speaker 1: To provide the FDA-approved Pfizer-Viagra AGV.

Speaker 2: And it took Pfizer about 10 years to come up with this formula.

Speaker 1: And it's the inactive ingredients that, okay, it kicks in faster.

Speaker 2: People are saying they feel it kick in in about 11 to 15 minutes.

Speaker 1: But on the bottle, it will say take one hour prior to get the best results.

Speaker 2: And then it lasts in your system longer.

Speaker 1: It lasts in your system for 14 hours.

Speaker 2: And less side effects are being reported, especially less headaches and that flushed feeling.

Speaker 1: Can I ask you, how is it different than Viagra that's on the market right now,

Speaker 2: either the brand name or the generic name?

Speaker 1: Yeah, so it's the inactive ingredients in Pfizer's AGV that makes it more powerful.

Speaker 2: So the best way for me to describe it is say if you had two cups of water and you had a generic Viagra

Speaker 1: and you had an AGV.

Speaker 2: You put the generic in a cup of water, it's going to dissolve in 30 seconds.

Speaker 1: You put the AGV in a cup of water, it's going to dissolve in two to three minutes.

Speaker 2: So that means when you swallow it, it allows it more time to get down to your member

Speaker 1: and work more effectively.

Speaker 2: The other question I have, I have type 2 diabetes.

Speaker 1: Is this supposedly helping with that a little bit more than the generic or the brand name?

Speaker 2: Yes, it should, yes.

Speaker 1: Yeah, a lot of people have type 2 diabetes and it works out great for them.

Speaker 2: And the other question I have is ordering it with you people, am I locked into refills

Speaker 1: or can that be just one order?

Speaker 2: So what happens is it does put you on automatic refills, but you don't have to have that.

Speaker 1: So what you can do is a lot of people just like to go ahead and put that on a six-month hold.

Speaker 2: That way it keeps your prescription active and your profile open with the doctor

Speaker 1: and just allows you to call in.

Speaker 2: You kind of cut out there for a little while so I didn't hear what you said.

Speaker 1: Oh, okay.

Speaker 2: It does come with automatic refills, but you don't have to have it set up that way.

Speaker 1: You have the option, a lot of people just like to go ahead and pause their refills for six months.

Speaker 2: That way it just keeps your prescription active and allows you to call in whenever you need a refill.

Speaker 1: Because every time people cancel, we have to end the cancel and then they call back to place another order,

Speaker 2: we have to pay the doctor's.

Speaker 1: You don't have to pay the doctor's fees, we cover that, but we have to pay them.

Speaker 2: So that's why it's just better to pause it.

Speaker 1: Speaking of doctor, as I potentially would fill this prescription,

Speaker 2: do I have to see a doctor or is it just through your support staff?

Speaker 1: Yes.

Speaker 2: So what happens is I take your order and I ask you a couple questions for the doctors to review.

Speaker 1: We have licensed doctors.

Speaker 2: And then once you place your order, they will review your profile

Speaker 1: and we need a list of all the medications, like prescription medications you're on.

Speaker 2: And if you have any questions, you can reach out to the clinician,

Speaker 1: and if they have any questions, they'll reach out to you.

Speaker 2: Once they approve your prescription, it goes to our pharmacy called Go-Go Meds in Kentucky,

Speaker 1: and they ship it out to you from there.

Speaker 2: They will email you a tracking number, and you usually get it in about five days or less.

Speaker 1: And is there a fee?

Speaker 2: Do I have to pay for that doctor review of the information?

Speaker 1: No.

Speaker 2: So we cover the doctor's fees.

Speaker 1: The pharmacy just charges a $14.95 processing fee.

Speaker 2: So we have a quantity of 40 for $149, with the pharmacy fee comes out to $163.95.

Speaker 1: And then we have a quantity of 25 for $99, with the fee comes out to $113.95.

Speaker 2: And then they also come in 25, 50, and 100 milligrams, and it's all the same price.

Speaker 1: So I always say you should just go for the hundreds, and you can break them in half if you need to.

Speaker 2: Okay.

Speaker 1: I had called a couple weeks ago, and the price that you're offering now is significantly higher than what I heard before.

Speaker 2: Yeah, because they didn't include the pharmacy fee.

Speaker 1: Well, actually, it was even with that.

Speaker 2: I was told for 10 tablets, it would be approximately $40.

Speaker 1: Okay, 10 tablets is $49.

Speaker 2: With the pharmacy processing fee, it comes out to $63.95.

Speaker 1: Okay.

Speaker 2: Well, you've answered my questions, and I'll review it and call back to you, okay?

Speaker 1: All right.

Speaker 2: Sounds good.

Speaker 1: Have a great day.

Speaker 2: Thank you.

Speaker 1: Bye.
